---
title: Salmon Limone with Couscous, Italian Herbs & Zucchini Ribbon Salad
description: Limone is Italian for lemon, so you know this fish dish is going to have some vitamin-C-packing sour power. But that’s only the start of it: there are veggies and herbs and beautiful fillets, too. Bubbly Israeli couscous is toasted and simmered with a little butter. Then, the salmon is dusted with our Italian seasoning and pan-seared. But the real showstopper might be the zucchini ribbon salad, which is as pretty as it is delightfully refreshing (and fun to twirl around your fork).
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/614b477d07c2532eb677c09c-a12c2ae7.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/salmon-limone-614b477d07c2532eb677c09c-47788111.pdf
author: Michelle Doll Olson
servings: 2
cuisine: Italian
nutrition:
  calories: 800 kcal
  fat: 51 g
  saturated fat: 15 g
  carbohydrates: 52 g
  sugar: 8 g
  protein: 36 g
  fiber: 6 g
  sodium: 320 mg
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/salmon-limone-614b477d07c2532eb677c09c
time required: 20 minutes
course: main course
---

Wash and dry produce. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Dice @roma tomato{1}.

Melt @butter{1%tbsp} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add @Israeli couscous{1/2%cup}, scallion whites, and @Italian seasoning{1/2%tsp}; cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Pour in @water{3/4%cup}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, and a pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until couscous is al dente, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Drain any excess liquid if necessary. Cover #pot{} and set aside.

Meanwhile, pat @salmon{10%oz} dry with #paper towels{}. Season all over with remaining @Italian seasoning{1/2%tbsp}, salt, and @pepper{}.

Heat @butter{1%tbsp} and @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a large, preferably nonstick, #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add salmon skin sides down; cook until skin is crispy, ~{5-7%minutes}. Flip and cook until fish is opaque and cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes} more. Remove from pan and set aside.

While salmon cooks, using a #peeler{}, shave @zucchini{1} lengthwise into ribbons, rotating as you go, until you get to the seedy core; discard core. Zest and quarter @lemon{1}.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine scallion greens, tomato, and zucchini ribbons. Add a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp} and juice from half the lemon. Season generously with salt and pepper. Toss to combine.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{2%tbsp}, @lemon zest{1/4%tsp}, salt, and pepper. Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

Fluff couscous with a #fork{}; stir in remaining lemon zest. Season with salt and pepper.

Divide couscous between #bowls{} or plates; top with salmon and salad. Drizzle crema over everything. Serve with remaining lemon wedges on the side.

> Limone is Italian for lemon, so this dish has vitamin-C-packing sour power along with veggies, herbs, and beautiful fillets.

> Bubbly Israeli couscous is toasted and simmered with a little butter, then the salmon is dusted with Italian seasoning and pan-seared.

> The zucchini ribbon salad is as pretty as it is delightfully refreshing (and fun to twirl around your fork).